      },
      "date": "2020-08-20 05:17:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Wang, WC checkpatch does not use \"--strict\" parameter when checking pushed patches. Effectively the limit is now 100. When is the --strict mode used? What I mean is --strict mode is now redundant (for column breach check). Maybe a directive to mark long lines to be ignored would be more appropriate here IMHO. On other hand I thought 80 cols work great when I am splitting my vi vertically :)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "eb5b482d3db1e621cfa7ceb837bc3157ce19a058",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 428,
        "name": "Wang Shilong",
        "email": "wangshilong1991@gmail.com",
        "username": "wangshilong",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2020-08-20 05:49:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Hi Wang, WC checkpatch does not use \"--strict\" parameter when\n > checking pushed patches. Effectively the limit is now 100. When is\n > the --strict mode used? What I mean is --strict mode is now\n > redundant (for column breach check). Maybe a directive to mark long\n > lines to be ignored would be more appropriate here IMHO. On other\n > hand I thought 80 cols work great when I am splitting my vi\n > vertically :)\n\nI had no preferences here, just follow upstream behavior.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
